This is my newest painting "Trellis" on view right now at CONTEXT in Miami. I've been thinking a lot about the idea of value and when making this piece I was thinking about it being at one of the world's largest art weeks. I can imagine how this idea is heighted in such a setting with a vast range of precious and valuable objects being exhibited and exchanged. 

"Trellis" is a step in a new direction.  You might have noticed that besides a candle or two I omit manmade objects in my art. For this piece I wanted to imagine what we might protect if it was something we humans thought of as valuable. Our natural world is the most precious part of our lives because it is literally the land we stand on, water we drink, and air we breathe.  What if we treated nature like a Faberge Egg - a delicate and precious object of unique quality and immense value?  We would certainly make sure it was safe and protect it from harm.  In other words we'd live in a much more sustainable way with our planet.  This painting is my way of showcasing nature and its future as a precious object. 

Check it out @coreyhelfordgallery in Booth B9 this week through Sunday Dec 4 at 
Context Art Miami Pavilion in Downtown Miami.  From what I've seen so far, the other artists really showed up with some fantastic works. 

#contextartmiami #coreyhelfordgallery #artmiami #artbasel #artbaselmiami

This piece is called “Hygge,” a Danish word that describes cozy contentment and something that part of the world must be settling into during these winter months. As I was walking around my neighborhood and passing by prickly pear cacti, I let my mind wander and imagined a Los Angeles submerged underwater.  After all, it is the Los Angeles basin and was once underwater.  Thoughts of new habitats for sea life splashed into my mind and I made this painting. Rather than the stingy tentacles of an anemone for protection, these clownfish now use the cactus to find a safe place to call home and get snuggly.

Last night I got to meet the collector who bought it and after a nice conversation realized it was waiting for *this* home, which surely would have found another had I painted it earlier.  I love how things work out like that. 
It got me thinking how special it is to know where my painting go after the gallery. For the most part, unless the collector gets in touch (which I love) I never know where my babies go. So it’s nice to know this little one is in great hands.

This is my latest painting, "Nagamorphoss," part of the @beautifulbizarremagazine curated exhibition 'Secret Longings' at @coreyhelfordgallery which opened last night!  The opening was a blast and it was so good to see some old and new friends. 

At its core, this piece is about becoming your heightened self.  Transforming into the enlightened version you've longed and worked for.  In Hinduism and Buddhism, the naga (snake creatures) are supernatural and powerful creatures that serve as protectors.  My snake here is bestowing divine powers and transforming this hummingbird into its "super saiyan" self.  Luna moths hide among the gingko leaves hinting at this transformation. 

A big thank you to @danijelakrhapurssey and @sherrijtrahan for including me in this show and counting me amongst these amazing artists. 
The show runs troughs April 15th, so make sure to check it out!!

Now's the time to kokua and ACT for Hawaiian birds; it's NOW or NEVER.  This Friday March 24th, the Board of Land and Natural Resources (BLNR) will request authorization to issue a finding of no significant impact of @birdsnotmosquitoes efforts to stabilize and recover populations of critically endangered Hawaiian forest birds.  This is the last chance to fight avian malaria for a number of Hawaiian honeycreepers that are projected to go extinct within the next 2-5 years.  

Please take some time to submit written testimony by 3/23 and sign up to testify orally (via Zoom).⁠ It's crucial you let the board know that our manu (birds) are important to you and Hawai'i.

To provide testimony via Zoom (preferred method to make an impact):
Email blnr.testimony@hawaii.gov with your name and “agenda item C2”. You will receive an email response with the zoom link.

To provide written testimony:
Email your testimony to blnr.testimony@hawaii.gov⁠
The meeting will be viewable at https://www.youtube.com/@boardoflandandnaturalresou1484 ⁠
Important notes to mention in the testimony include:
-The Environmental Assessment is thorough and outlines the proper procedure to implement Incompatible Insect Technique (mosquito birth control) in Hawaiʻi
-BLNR should agree with the finding of no significant impact and vote to approve
⁠
You can follow links in my bio to the final environmental assessment report and the agenda for Friday's meeting.  

Mahalo nui for speaking for native birds and being a steward of nature.  And Mahalo to  @birdsnotmosquitoes and @laulimahawaii for the important info.

social_posts.post_text: Today I celebrate 15 years with the love of my life. From starting out as my best friend and now the mother of my baby, she’s the best partner anyone could ask for. I’m the artist and human I am today because of her endless love and support and if you like anything I do, you have her to thank. Her impeccable intuition, fierce sense of justice, and untouchable taste in music and all things cool are so inspiring. Plus her beauty makes me weak in the knees and causes me to constantly ask myself how I got so lucky to end up with such a babe. I love you so much @caseyjohanna and am so grateful to have you as my soulmate. Thanks for asking me out properly 15 years ago and not just pretending we were dating like I did. We’ve already had a lifetime of adventures together and I’m giddy thinking about all that well do in the next 15 years!

Today is a day to celebrate!  After a lot of testimony from across Hawai'i from community members, scientist, conservationist and even keiki, the Board of Land and Natural Resources voted unanimously to give our manu (birds) a shot at a future, opening the road for @birdsnotmosquitoes to implement the wolbachia IIT program.  This will be HUGE in suppressing avian malaria as climate change allows invasive mosquitos into higher elevations, the last refuge for the honeycreepers.  

It was inspiring and heart touching to see so many use their voices for the voiceless and express love and acknowledgment of these endemic forest birds who have existed well before us. Even the board members got emotional, recognizing this important moment. 

The traditional Hawaiian greeting of touching noses and exchanging breath is called "Honi". I painted this scene of an 'akikiki honi the extinct 'o'o as a way of expressing the critical state of the 'akikiki as it greets its lost sibling.  Sadly, there likely isn't enough time for 'akikiki which is projected to go extinct this year, but this program can save the others!  It’s a huge step in this right direction and I hope for all the success of this program in bringing Hawaii’s endemic birds back from the brink.

When I first learned about the teeny tiny pygmy seahorse, I thought about how the coral polyps it has evolved to resemble looked like cherry blossom buds and how fun it would be to hide one amongst the blossoming branches. Though there are only 400 of them today, it’s larger than it was 20 years ago when there were less than 100 in 2002. This uplifting example of conservation efforts and recovery shows us that in many cases, extinction is a choice and we can choose to do the work to not lose species forever.

Todays the day my newest show “Terra Brio” opens @havengallery!  Here’s my piece “Arroyo” where new live is thriving in a flooded desert. 

It’s always a bittersweet moment when the show opens. On one hand, I’m relieved to have months of work and sacrifice completed and all the checklists crossed out. In the last few years, California’s superblooms have become famous with hills of wildflowers bursting all at once, creating a painted landscape we can see from space. It’s truly a beautiful thing to behold. This is a result of long periods of dry conditions coming to a temporary end with heavy rainfall, like the record breaking storms we had this year. While I was making this show during these epic storms I couldn’t help but think about the impending superblooms and what happens in the summer. The overgrowth of vegetation dries up and becomes an abundant source of fuel for wildfires. What was once a dreamworld of flowers potentially turns into dystopia. And yet, fire is a natural part of life on this planet that enriches the soil and creates the conditions for life to rebound and thrive.  

‘Torch’ is part my current solo and showing @havengallery right now. This Friday there will be a reception at the gallery from 5-8PM.  I so wish I could be there, but timing didn’t work in my favor this time.  This is piece is one of two that are still available. To inquire please get in touch with Erica at info@havengallery.com.

This new painting is called "In Plain Sight.” A lot of my work has to do with finding the magic in nature, painting surreal and supernatural scenes realistically as if you could stumble upon them IRL if you looked a little closer. That's what I love about geodes.  On the outside they look mundane but hidden within, just out of sight, is a crystalline feast for the eyes!  In this piece, that geode transforms into a stalk of flowers, a metaphor for the life force of this rock we live on and the life that grows because of it.  As the chameleon discovers this treasure, it transforms its form by growing crystals to be more in harmony with the earth. This is the transformation I want to see in the world. One where we transform ourselves to be more in sync with the planet. For me, this piece is a reminder of that goal and I hope it can serve that purpose for you too.

You can find this available now as a 16x20" print on my website. And you can view this and the other paintings it inspired in my current show "Terra Brio" showing @havengallery now through June 4th.  Thanks!

Also, big shout out to the amazing @kanekokaris, master of scales and details, who helped me navigate painting all those scales. Thanks mate for your time and guidance. One day I’ll paint as good you..one day!

Today is Endangered Species Day and I'd like to highlight a success story that inspired this painting "Keystone" from a few years back.  In the 1800s as westward expansion took over wildlands, gray wolves were killed almost to extinction to protect livestock. But the Endangered Species Act of 1973 helped the wolves recover and they were reintroduced to Yellowstone Park in 1995, which changed the face of the park itself.  Wolves are keystone species (a species on which other species and they ecosystem largely depend) and their presence in the habitat controlled deer populations and movement.  This stopped them from overgrazing, which allowed forests to grow back quickly, creating habitat for birds and woodland animals from rabbits to bears.  The rivers even changed as beavers attracted by the new tree growth built dams and the tree systems stabilized the ground, allowing water to flow more regularly and back to their ancestral paths, benefiting the habitat and wildlife even more.  And this was all due in a short amount of time with only 31 wolves put back.  

This world is so interconnected and this success story of us deciding to stop our destructive behavior, put things back in place and take our hands off of it is one that can be told for so many species.  We are in a mass extinction crisis right now with an estimated 150 species going extinct EVERY DAY! We need to save our biodiversity, especially keystone species which will lead to saving many more species.

This piece is called ‘Cerebro.’  If you’ve ever seen raw silicon (not to be confused with silicone) you'll know it’s this shiny, bluish, chrome hunk of an element. This chemical element and its amazing superconducting properties have drastically changed our lives, making it possible for this post to exist in the first place. Found in all of our devices, it has connected our minds to everything and arguably altered our neurology.  Like all great technologies, it has made paths to both good and bad.  It is part of us and our appetite is only growing. 

'Cerebro' is part of my current show 'Terra Brio' showing @havengallery now through June 4th.  Please check out this and the other works through the link in my bio and inquire with Erica - info@havengallery.com

I think like most kids, genies captivated my young imagination, especially growing up with the movie Aladdin.  How cool would it be to stumble upon the lottery of all lotteries and have 3 of your wildest wishes come true in an instant? As an adult I still find myself daydreaming of having my deepest wishes manifest.  An instant change to a carbon-free world.  All the endangered species we've killed and their habitats restored.  An endless supply of cookies and ice cream...I gotta do one just for me, right?  What would you wish for? 

This piece is called 'Djinn' and is part of my current show 'Terra Brio’ @havengallery on view through June 4th.  Thank you to everyone who has checked out the work and thank *YOU* for following along and supporting my art.  I really appreciate all the love you share with me here.  There are a couple of really cool pieces still available from the show which you can inquire about with Erica - info@havengallery.com.  Mahalo!

Take a look at the finishing touch of my piece, ‘Arachnitite’. Do you see the 👀👀👀👀?

Happy World Oceans Day!  What would Earth be with its oceans?  It’s our treasure and our life force. Let’s celebrate it everyday and pledge to protect it. The start is saving 30% by 2030. As catchy as 30x30 is, it’s kind of crazy to think that saving only 30% of anything, let alone the thing that enables LIFE on this planet, is enough. We can do more!

#worldoceansday #30x30 #conservation

I had the distinct honor of working with @suntupeditions to illustrate the incredible story of LIFE OF PI by master storyteller Yann Martel.  It is truly one of my favorites books full of heart, adventure, philosophy, magic and perseverance and it was a dream to work on this project.  The book, which itself is a piece of artwork, is offered in 3 editions and features 6 of the paintings I made for it, with the Classic Edition including this dust jacket.  These fine press limited editions are available for pre-order now!  Click the link in my bio to see and learn more.

Here's a closer look at the dust cover image I made for Life of Pi.  This was compositionally a fun challenge for me as I needed the piece to wrap around the book while having the focus be weighted to the right.  I also rarely do landscape oriented painting, so this one took a while to put together.  But I couldn't be happier with the outcome.  It has just the right amount of magical realism in harmony with the book and there's lots of little details from the story hidden throughout.

This is my portrait of Richard Parker, the tiger from Life of Pi.  In the book, Pi discovers that in addition to his Hindu upbringing, he also finds god in Islam and Christianity, adopting all three faiths as his own.  And since Richard Parker and Pi have such an intimate relationship, I thought I'd project those faiths onto the tiger in this piece.  The dove wings, mughal halo and marigold lei represent these three religions forming a sort of new Holy Trinity. 

All three Suntup editions of Life of Pi by Yann Martel are now sold out. Congratulations @suntupeditions!

#lifeofpi #yannmartel #suntupeditions #richardparker

How meta. I’m painting bleached coral while listening to The Daily podcast about bleached coral. I’m really glad they did an episode about the extremely hot water in Florida and how that just killed off a ton of corals. And it’s not even the hottest time of year. 25% of all marine life depends on corals reefs. We depend on marine life to survive. Use the transitive property. 

#coralbleaching #coralreef  #globalwarming #climateawareness

This is “Neogenesis” from my show last September.  In many cultures’ origin stories, the turtle or tortoise plays a key role as the foundation for life to grow on. I love this because it acknowledges that turtles and the other animals were here before us. They are our kupuna, our ancestors. And not only were they here before, they are the reason we have life. 

In this piece, what looks like a beach is actually a flooded desert. Our future world we’re walking into will be a more watery one and once again, the turtle is here to be the substrate of life on this new beginning. Maybe we can be the woodpeckers that reseed the land.

My show "A Thousand Invisible Cords," opens tomorrow @kpprojectsgallery. The title refers to a John Muir quote about the interconnectedness of everything on our beautifully balanced planet and that was my guiding light in making this show.  Some pieces stand alone while others are in conversation with each other.  Some are about pure joy and bliss while others confront harder topics. All of it makes up the complexities of our natural world and indeed our human world too.  

This piece is one where I hope the idea of balance resonates. I want to leave the specifics open to allow your thoughts to come through, but my general thoughts are about how finding balance can lead to rebirth and that darkness is sometimes necessary for there to be light.  

Join me TOMORROW! Wait what, it's December already?!!  I can't wait for the show to open and hope everyone local can swing by the show.  Come through LA! 

Siren Call
20”x16”, oil on wood
Inquiries: preview@kpprojects.net

One reason I like to blur the line between air and water is to highlight the interconnection of nature that crosses these elemental lines. All of life exists in one or the other and all of life is dependent on both. And I specifically love air and water because of how things flow in the two different yet similar fluids. 

This piece is about things coming together to form balance, completing the whole and creating something new and magical. It’s part of my current solo “A Thousand Invisible Cords” now exhibiting @kpprojectsgallery. 

•Coalesce•
Oil on wood
16” tondo

This piece is called Adaptive Radiation, a biological term that refers to the rapid evolution of new species from a single, rapid diversifying lineage each with its own specialized way of life - think Hawaii’s Honeycreepers or New Guinea’s Birds of Paradise.  When a species is free from predation and allowed to find how it perfectly fits in with its habitat, a beautiful symbiosis and transformation occurs.  In a way, my flauna creatures are all part of this phenomenon, exemplifying the boundlessness of evolution. 

Adaptive Radiation
Oil on wood
24”x18”

This is my reef healer.  I was inspired by the ancient turtle I met while scuba diving in Bali this past summer (swipe to the end to see). This divine turtle with its healing powers brings life back to the bleached reef and as it glides across the coral, color and life bloom back and the fish return to a thriving habitat.  As a habitat dies, so does the life it supports and to make this point, I played with the idea of “bleached” fish.  Color is the indication of life and these ghost fishes represent what is lost when coral dies.  The reef healer has a big job to do but it is fulfilling its kuleana (responsibility and duty) to care for the earth, an example humans need to follow. 

Resuscitation
Oil on wood
40”x30”

This is a new piece called Transference.  It’s an idea I’ve wanted to paint for a while now because almost every time I see a Turkey Tail Mushroom the concentric layers remind me of an agate geode’s layers, and vice versa.  These visual homophones (is there a word that means two things looks a like?) remind me that all things are connected and the wonder of nature ties them all together.  And the mutualistic symbiosis of fungi and tree are certainly one of the coolest wonders we’ve been able to figure out.  A connection so invisible yet so important to such a fundamental part of life seems like the best definition of magic that I can think of! 

Transference
Oil on wood
16”x12”

Looking back on 2023 has got me looking back even further and I thought it was the perfect time to share this new piece.  This is the flauna creature where it all started. My Frida bird.  This galah/peony was the first flauna creature I ever made and I haven’t stopped exploring this idea ever since.  I first made her for one of my earliest group shows at @wonderlandsf aka the legendary icon @irenehfeiks.  I was inspired by Frida and how she always had flowers in her hair and had sketched a piece with the cockatoo adorned with flowers.  But when I sat down to paint it I realized I could just make the feathers into flower petals and on the spot changed the piece.  That piece set me off on this journey and now having my current solo at KP Projects marks a very high point of that journey. So for this show I wanted to bring back this character and see what she looks like now, 7 years later. 

Here’s a look at the my piece “Wonderland” followed by the first piece “Flowers In Her Hair” and a reference I used, “Self Portrait as a Tehuana” by Frida Kahlo.  There’s one more week to view my show “A Thousand Invisible Cords” @kpprojectsgallery.  Thank you all so much for your amazing support and joining along in this journey!  I hope you have the very best start to 2024!!

Wonderland
Oil on wood
24”x20”

My show closes this Saturday 1/6 and I’m planning to be at the gallery at some point then to say goodbye and send off my work with well wishes.  And this is something I didn’t think I’d physically be able to do just a week ago.  This past month has been one of the most intense of my life.  I went from a career high as my show opened with such a great turn out and sales I didn’t even dare dream of to being bedridden just a couple weeks later.  I’ve been in and out of doctors appointments to learn that my spine has several issues putting me in the most excruciating pain I’ve ever experienced.  It was a living nightmare.  On top of that, a friend’s unexpected passing and my landlords being complete heartless dicks made the last weeks of 2023 extremely difficult.  But by some chance of luck my pain started to go away and with a procedure under my belt I’m on my way to recovery.  Fingers crossed I can find my way back to normal life soon and start painting again. The pandemic taught me this lesson and this trial is enforcing it: be grateful everyday you have your health.  Celebrate it and don’t take it for granted.

It’s been 5 months since the Lahaina wildfire killed nearly 100 people, destroyed Lahaina Town and permanently altered the lives of so many more.  I made this piece shortly after the fire as a way of processing that tragedy and finding a sliver of hope.  Here, an ‘Akohekohe (an endangered, endemic Hawaiian honeycreeper) native to Maui is perched on the burning, hanging roots of the banyan tree.  The bird itself is helping to heal the tree, a symbol of Lahaina Town, absorbing and smoldering the fire in its form while promoting regrowth.  I held hope and aloha that the tree would start to regrow and indeed it has new leaves sprouting and there are signs that birds are starting to nest in its canopy again.  The resilience of nature is one I always look to when things seem dire and though it will take a long time for the people of west Maui and Lahaina to rebuild, they will.  Tread softly and respectfully if you visit that area.  It may not be in the news anymore, but healing takes time and residents there are still trying to find a way forward. 

Lahaina
Oil on wood
16” tondo
